description: 1640–1650: from French prolifique, from Latin proles (“offspring”) and facere (“to make”).

adjectives.description: prolific (comparative more prolific, superlative most prolific)

entries.meaning: Fertile; producing offspring or fruit in abundance — applied to plants producing fruit, animals producing young, etc.
Similarly producing results or performing deeds in abundance
examples: However appealing Antibes may be to migrant authors, indigenous ones are relatively scarce. A notable exception is Jacques Audiberti, Antibes-born novelist and prolific playwright who wrote in the turn-of-the-century surrealist style, with titles that translate as Slaughter, or In Favour of Infanticide.

entries.meaning: (botany) Of a flower: from which another flower is produced.
